prefix: Approach the following question the way someone in elementary school would.
problem_prompt: Approach the following question the way someone in elementary school would. What percent of the positive integers less than or equal to $100$ have no remainders when divided by $5?$
solution: The only numbers that leave no remainder when divided by $5$ are those that are divisible by $5$. Starting from $1,$ every five integers is divisible by $5: 5,10,15,\ldots$ This continues even until the last group of five numbers $96$ through $100$ where $100$ is divisible by $5$. Therefore, since we have a whole number of groups of five and every group has exactly one element that is divisible by $5$, $1/5 = \boxed{20}$ percent of the integers less than $100$ have no remainders when divided by $5$.
gpt_response:
To find out how many numbers have no remainders when divided by $5$, we can see that every fifth number is divisible by $5$. So, to find out how many of the first $100$ numbers are divisible by $5$, we can do $100 \div 5 = 20$. 

So, $20$ out of the $100$ numbers have no remainders when divided by $5$. To find the percent, we just do $\frac{20}{100} \times 100 = 20\%$.

Therefore, $20\%$ of the positive integers less than or equal to $100$ have no remainders when divided by $5$.
